# Networking Devices — Routers, Hubs, Access Points

**Date:** January 5,2026.


## What even is networking

Computers talking to each other using agreed rules. Thats it.
Those agreed rules are called protocols. Everything else — the devices,
the cables, the layers — exists to make that communication work reliably.


## Access Point (AP)

An access point is interesting because it does three jobs at once —
it acts as a router, a switch, and a wireless access point simultaneously.

Its basically the bridge between your wired Ethernet network and wireless
devices. Without it, your laptop and phone would have no way to join a
network that runs on physical cables.

From a pentesting angle, APs are juicy targets. Weak encryption (WEP/WPA),
default credentials, evil twin attacks — wireless is its own whole attack
surface.


## Hub — why it matters even though nobody uses it

Hubs are old and basically dead. But i think its worth understanding them
because they perfectly illustrate why uncontrolled traffic is a problem.

A hub has zero intelligence. When it receives data it broadcasts it to
every single device on the network. Every device sees every packet,
whether its meant for them or not.

This is a nightmare for two reasons:

1. Performance collapses as more devices join
2. Any device on the network can see traffic meant for someone else

Thats actually how early network sniffing worked. Plug into a hub-based
network and you passively receive everything. Switches killed this by
being smarter about where they send traffic — but the concept is why
promiscuous mode and packet capture tools still matter.


## Router

A router takes data from one IP subnet and moves it into another.
Thats the core job.

Its referred to as a Layer 3 device because it operates at the Network
layer of the OSI model — dealing with IP addresses rather than
MAC addresses.

Two terms that keep coming up:

- **LAN** (Local Area Network) — your internal network, the devices in
  your house or office
- **WAN** (Wide Area Network) — the internet, or connections between
  geographically separate networks

Routers sit at the boundary between these. They decide where packets go
based on routing tables and IP addresses.


